description.text: Having used Apple computers all my life starting with a //e I felt like I needed to print SOMETHING to honor Steve Jobs. Based on http://sketchup.google.com/3dwarehouse/details?mid=4b3607f3cde3037658fc1ad354006c7 I modified that to make it more printable, scaled it to size, and added the classic apple logo to the front of the screen. I'm skeining it right now to see how it prints. Enjoy

A few hours later....Print is going, I've edited the file several times to tweak some details.
Every member of the original Macintosh team had their signatures injection molded on the inside of the cases of some of the computers. I've added my twist on that as a memorial to the members of that team that are no longer with us, flip the computer over and you'll find their initials.
Jef Raskin, Brian Howard, and Steve Jobs rest in peace.

I've added another file "Mac Classic Support.stl" this one has two support walls under the lower overhang that should help the print.  I also added a mouse cable to link the two objects together.  The object as a whole is 87x111x83 so it should fit on a thing-o-matic without scaling.  I printed this with 0 infill and a few extra shells, make sure that you have infill set to 45 degrees so that when it prints the top surfaces the bridges come out better.  The very top works with 0 infill because its slightly pitched so it doesnâ€™t try to cover the whole thing at once.  
My first print of this didnâ€™t come out all that great (mostly because my prusa isn't working as well as it should).  I'm hoping to have time to print the new version soon.

description.text:
Replicated Miniature model of the Martinitoren in Groningen, The Netherlands
Original (wooden) model can be purchased at xsModelmakers.nl Two models included, all in one piece or separate pieces with some nubs and holes to fit the pieces together. The original model uses small magnets to stick together. Technical data:
Name: Martinitower
Buildyear: 1577
Location: Groningen, The Netherlands
Architect: Gerrit Kistemaker
Scale: 1:250
Total height: 320f / 97m PS: I've looked for half an hour to find out how the copyright would work in this case since it's an inexact replication of a very simplified model of an existing but very old building. If anyone knows more about this please leave a comment. If it turns out to be naughty I'll remove it.

Printer:

Velleman Vertex K8400

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.5mm

Infill:

10%

Notes: I printed at 0.1mm but the design details (except for the bulb on the top) are not more than 0.5 mm resolution. Since it's a sculpture (unless used as a toy) strength is not so important so I printed at 10% infill. Of course you could also make it out of wood using this model for measurements.

Finishing This is a very straightforward print, with mostly straight lines and very few overhangs. If you want to copy the original model, print it with woodlike material and use a gold-pen or something to paint the bulb. To copy the actual building you'll have to paint some more details. The one and only original. There is a 1.5m high model as well.

description.text:
Played a great game of backstabbing and had to put the million tokens of the game away?
Ever wondered if storing the tokens could have been made easier? Well this might be the thing for you, if you want less of a mess in your board game box.
These storage boxes are made to make your life easier, when assembling and putting away the game. The names of the files should be self explanatory to which tokens is to be put in the boxes. The following number of boxes are used to store the tokens (and cards): 1 influence, victory point and neutral force token box
1 supply, wildling and hourglass token box
1 order tokens box
2 card holders box
2 power tokens box What I used;
3Dprinter: M3D
Slicer: Cura 15.04.2
mat: PLA
infill : 5-100%
Layer height : 0.15
speed: 35 mm/s
No supports needed I hope these will make your board game nights less of a hassle, and if you like them please shoot me a comment (also if you find something wrong or anything, will try to fix it asap).
Feel free to customize them if you want, as long you give me a mention.
Happy board gaming! Note:
1) The calibration on my printer where waay off, resulting in the pretty bad quality on the top of the boxes, so take my pictures with a grain of salt.
2) These boxes have no lid, although I have models with the ability to add a lid already done. If anyone is interested, I will add them too.
3) Hopefully your backlash settings are better tweaked than mine, so the order token box has better circles than mine. Otherwise: Happy sanding... Edit:3.2.2016

This Ski design scales really well, I have printed sets as small as 40% for small fomies and as large as 130% for 40 to 60 size planes. The pictures are of version 2, which didn't have the rounded nose.
Print with 75 to 100% fill, with supports, 0.2 to 0.3mm layers, PLA prints well but may become brittle in real cold temperatures ABS or Nylon will tolerate the cold much better.
The holes may need to be drilled out if the scale is reduced. This design requires the use of a wheel collar, 2 is best but a single one will work, and the spring from a small clamp (use smaller springs for smaller skis) for each ski, I have also used the collar from a prop saver.
I replace the set screw in the wheel collar with a 12 to 16mm long 2mm or 3mm screw, only one collar per wheel needs this done.
For a 2 collar setup, put the one with the extended screw on the axel, for a one collar setup just put the ski on.
The spring needs to be bent, put the spring on the axel tight to the ski then put a mark on it, lined up with the front hole on the ski.
Bend the spring 90deg so that when installed the bent end will go into the front hole on the ski
Put the spring back on tight to the ski then put the collar on, you will need to mark the spring again and bend, first a 90deg bend and then a 3/4 loop in the end of it. the idea is to have the loop be able to hold the spring tight to the extended screw.
Once the bends are made put everything back on the axel, the angle of the ski can be set by loosening the collar and rotating it to tip the nose of the ski up slightly, about 5deg should be ideal but hard, rough snow conditions may require more.
Tighten the collar/s and enjoy the cold. I use http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:88569 to make custom springs to work with these skis

The Shy Rockabilly Extruder is a remix of the B'Struder universal Bowden extruder. The basic design ideas are the same but the remix allows for parametric modification of model details such as filament thickness and bearing details. The extruder arm has a lower profile and it requires only two bearings instead of original three. Like the original B'Struder, the Shy Rockabilly Extruder uses 623 bearings (only two needed). M3 nuts and screws are used for putting everything together. This variant is made for a Mk8 drive gear and a M5 threaded tube connector. Add a 10mm diameter spring to tension the arm. I have printed different design iterations from both ABS and PLA and both work fine with moderate infill. The extruder face can be printed as is. The arm can be printed upside down without supports or in the original orientation with supports enabled. Without supports, the bearing enclosures come out a bit messy but the arm is still usable. The design works flawlessly with my large kossel-style delta printer. The thing is designed using Autodesk Fusion 360. The original design files are available for modification here:

  • http://a360.co/1It9gq2

This is a remix of my gallon can spout.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:121655 This one has a spout that swivels. The spout snap-fits on to the threaded cap. The straight spout is better than nothing, but I think this curved spout has more utility. Since a can's threads may vary, and since a gasket or sealing washer may or may not be used, the cap orientation can vary, and the spout's direction can be adjusted accordingly. I printed this one in ABS, and the fit is good. The swivel is secure enough, and turns smoothly. The plan is to print one in nylon, which can be used with acetone and similarly volatile chemicals. Nylon is far more flexible than ABS, and its use may suggest a minor redesign. So, this project somewhat of a work in progress. I doubt there will be any substantial modifications to these files.
Photos and whatnot will be provided in the next few days. This post will likely be deleted at that time. If required, one can convert this SAE file to suit metric print software. Scale up by a factor of 25.4

I didn't like any of the boxes for JAWong's Setters tiles so I made my own.
This is setup for a 3-4 player set but you can print as many of the tall/short tile boxes as needed for 6+ players. I made these holders specifically to accommodate all of JAWong's original pieces (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:26979), as well as the unique pieces trire123 made (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1132283).

Box_V2 TallTiles.stl ----This box section holds the mountain(ore) tiles
Box_V2 ShortTiles.stl --This box section holds all 3D printed tiles except for the mountain tiles
BoxAB_V2.stl-------------Full box set printed as one object (for people with very large print beds)
BoxA_V2.stl -------------This is just one part of the box that I cut for my printer
BoxB_V2.stl -------------This is just one part of the box that I cut for my printer

Edit_3 12/26:
Added V4 files. I cleaned up the vertices, increased the tolerances to better accommodate painted pieces, and increased the perimeter wall thickness so that Slic3r doesn't screw up (slic3r apparently over fills thin walls). I think this will be the final draft. Edit_2 12/25:
Added the 123D file for anyone who wants to modify it. Edit_1 12/25:
Added V3 parts. They're more optimized, stronger, and use less plastic.

author: deadshort

title: Z Stabilizer Top-of-Rod Clamps (8 or 12mm rod)

description.text: After upgrading by Printrbot LC with longer (400mm) 8mm smooth rods and M5 threaded rod leadscrews, and installing z-axis stabilizers for the bottom of the rod (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:46082), I still wanted more stiffness. Other clamps on Thingiverse were not to my satisfaction. Some coupled the smooth rods together by clamping to a rod (or rods) that were not in the same vertical plane as the ones used for motion, creating unnecessary stress at the points where the rods are fastened. Others required a very specific length of rod, or were too bulky or heavy for my liking. For an open-frame FDM printer, like the Printrbot LC or LC+ (new and old), these allow you to use your old 8 or 12mm smooth rod or 5/16" threaded rod (the threaded rod would almost be too short, but should work) to couple your z-axis threaded rods together for increased stability. As you will lose approximately 1in of travel in the z-axis, these will work best if you have already extended your z-axis smooth and threaded rods (this can be done quite cheaply, for a total of $20-$30 in parts from Amazon).

These are designed to clamp to a rod of the same size as your smooth rods (8mm for Printrbot LC or 12mm for the LC+). Threaded rod or smooth rod can be used as long as it is close enough in size to be clamped to.   
Print 4 copies of this part (two for each rod), and fasten them using a total of eight 3/4" 6-32 machine screws and nuts (M4 could also be used). Be sure to check that your smooth rods are parallel (and not \ /) before tightening the stabilizers. Enjoy!

I made this for when I am taking aerial photos with my drone.  I fly the drone with the video monitor mounted to the "control" transmitter. It was made to accept the metal bar that is on the back of many hobby-quality transmitters.  (in my case it is a Futaba T12FGH)  It holds it securely and I had no trouble trusting it with my $800 transmitter.
